		<p>Dear Todd, Thankyou for your kind comments &#8211; very gratifying! Jane Philbrick&#8217;s work sounds intriguing, and reminds me of another collaborative project by a French artist called Anais Tondeur (visualizing the sound of graphite).</p>
<p>The movement of collaborations between artist and scientists keeps gaining greater momentum, and I think it very fruitful &#8211; in fact many of last year&#8217;s new intake on the Central Saint Martin&#8217;s M.A. Art &amp; Science had scientific &#8211; mostly biological or earth sciences &#8211; (&amp; not art) training &#8211; so the boundaries are ever more blurred. In fact, I tend to think that maths is in many ways an arts/philosophy discipline.</p>
<p>In this respect I am very grateful to John Baez for providing such a lively platform for sharing and discussing such ideas.</p>

