		<p>John Baez, I read your Azimuth posts (I have subscribed through email). Thanks for taking the time to create these wonderful posts. I enjoy reading on these varied topics and your refreshing approach to writing about math/physics/etc.</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/?replytocom=158712#respond' data-commentid="158712" data-postid="2" data-belowelement="div-comment-158712" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to williamsharkey" aria-label='Reply to williamsharkey'>Reply</a></div>
				</div>
				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-danielleegeisler odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-160291">
				<div id="div-comment-160291" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='https://0.gravatar.com/avatar/f48a6058aba0a2c8e1e3928559cd0e8f?s=32&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn"><a href='http://transistorbuddha.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>Prashanta</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/#comment-160291">24 March, 2020 at 8:00 am</a>		</div>

		<p>I&#8217;m a lover of science and technology who caught the social service bug at sixteen. Now I&#8217;m a yogi currently working on curating the knowledge of different wisdom traditions. I&#8217;m a devotee of the Renaissance and it&#8217;s championing of art and music, of what is abstractly beautiful. So my question is how can we protect the subtle assets of our world? I miss the world science fiction foretold in the Sixties and peaking with positivity of TNG. After fifty years I need to be able to be able to present to my friends and family what is going on in the world. I know children that I want to have a good shot of thriving and prosperity.<br />
I also serve as an organizer among the tetration and hyperoperations community. I specialize in iterated smooth functions <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=f%5En%28x%29+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=333333&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002" alt="f^n(x) " class="latex" />, which is more general than Arnold&#8217;s measure preserving definition of dynamics. A main focus has been working on the question, &#8220;do maps in general have flows?&#8221;, with application to the hyperoperators.<br />
My applied category question is given <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=f%28g%28x%29%29+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=333333&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002" alt="f(g(x)) " class="latex" /> being associated with the integer and set partitions through Faa Di Bruno&#8217;s formula, it is easy to demonstrate the association of <img src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=f%5En%28x%29+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=333333&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002" alt="f^n(x) " class="latex" /> to total partitions (Stanley), hierarchies(Flajolet) and Schroeder&#8217;s Fourth Problem.<br />
Question &#8211; given the connection between set partitions and total partitions (not proved here), and the relationship of total partitions to Classification Theory, can the laws of physics be viewed as a classification engine? R. Aldrovandi and L. P. Freitas, Continuous iteration of dynamical maps, J. Math. Phys. 39, 5324 (1998) discuss the flow of dynamics through channels of greater and greater detail.</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/?replytocom=160291#respond' data-commentid="160291" data-postid="2" data-belowelement="div-comment-160291" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Prashanta" aria-label='Reply to Prashanta'>Reply</a></div>
				</div>
				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-163370">
				<div id="div-comment-163370" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='https://2.gravatar.com/avatar/858c08159451280b5c973d4d4bc6ac01?s=32&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn">Darrin Meyer</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/#comment-163370">25 July, 2020 at 6:43 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>There is a practical solution to many of the problems created by Climate Change.<br />
REDUCE SEA-LEVEL RISE BY HALF<br />
Due to increased glacier melting and thermal expansion, the Ocean is rising 3-4 mm per year &#8211; equivalent to 300 trillion gallons per year. At the same time, rivers pour hundreds of trillions of gallons of fresh water annually into the Ocean.<br />
For example, the watershed feeding James Bay, connected to Hudson Bay, pours 85 trillion gallons of fresh water into the Ocean per year; and the Columbia River in Oregon adds 65 trillion gallons annually.<br />
Even with continuing excess glacier melt, diverting 150 trillion gallons of water per year from these two sources will reduce the rate of sea-level rise by half.<br />
IRRIGATE ARID/SEMI-ARID MIDWEST REGIONS<br />
The water from James Bay can be diverted by canal to irrigate 500,000 sq. kilometers (125 million acre) of arid/semi-arid land stretching from Montana to Texas. The irrigation will approximate 18-24 inches per year of precipitation over the region.<br />
The Columbia River water can likewise be diverted by canal to irrigate the San Joaquin Valley in California (5-10 trillion gallons); and 300,000 sq. kilometers (75 million acres) in the arid part of Northern Nevada and Utah.<br />
FORESTS RECAPTURE ANNUAL U.S. CARBON OUTPUT<br />
The irrigated land in both regions can be used to grow billions of trees. Using half of the combined areas would create 100 million acres of new forests, which would recapture 60-80 tons of carbon per acre, or a total of 6-8 Billion tons per year &#8211; more than the total annual carbon output of the U.S.<br />
PROMOTE SMALL FARMS/OPPORTUNITY ZONES<br />
80 million acres (40% of the combined regions) could be set aside to revive small family farming. The remaining 20 million acres could be divided into 3,000  communities (+30 million people) drawing remote employees from tech industries and disadvantaged people who are frightened and sickened by life in decaying cities. The increase in land value of $8-10,000.00 per acre (approx. $2 Trillion) will more than offset the cost of building the canals.<br />
Darrin F. Meyer, Esq.</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/?replytocom=163370#respond' data-commentid="163370" data-postid="2" data-belowelement="div-comment-163370" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Darrin Meyer" aria-label='Reply to Darrin Meyer'>Reply</a></div>
				</div>
				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
