		<p>Just read your Azimuth piece about discounting.  IMO valuation of money may be temporally non-linear but should be integrable, contra Marx and other systems that ban interest. Rates are semiotic signals of the time value of money, something Marx denied. USUALLY people value &#8216;a bird in hand&#8217; more than &#8216;a bird in the bush,&#8217; but not always. So the usual thing, as with bonds, is that rates vary directly (or polynomially?) with duration. Best wishes!</p>

