		<p>You seem to have moved a bit back to physics from the Azimuth project, but that is based only on what I’ve read here recently.</p>
<p>Since Max Tegmark has moved from physics to AI, with the main goal to make AI safe, and is otherwise interested in saving the planet and so on and is in a position to actually influence some people, it seems that you should investigate possible synergy,</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/?replytocom=168616#respond' data-commentid="168616" data-postid="2" data-belowelement="div-comment-168616" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Phillip Helbig" aria-label='Reply to Phillip Helbig'>Reply</a></div>
				</div>
				<ul class="children">
		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-johncarlosbaez bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 highlander-comment" id="comment-168626">
				<div id="div-comment-168626" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='https://0.gravatar.com/avatar/34784534843022b3541c8ddd693718cb?s=32&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32' height='32' width='32' />			<cite class="fn"><a href='http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>John Baez</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/#comment-168626">5 January, 2021 at 8:21 pm</a>		</div>

		<p>For the last 5 years my main work on the Azimuth Project has been on &#8220;applied category theory&#8221;: a project to get category theorists doing more practical things, and to use category theory to develop <a href="https://medium.com/disruptive-design/tools-for-systems-thinkers-the-6-fundamental-concepts-of-systems-thinking-379cdac3dc6a" rel="nofollow ugc">systems thinking</a> in a more rigorous way.  This seems to be working well, so let me show off a bit.</p>
<p>There&#8217;s now an annual conference and school on Applied Category Theory!   The 2021 school includes two courses that use my work on <a href="https://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/structured/" rel="nofollow ugc">&#8220;structured cospans&#8221;</a>.   One of them uses structured cospans as part of a software tool that allows one to quickly build models from smaller parts:</p>
<p>&bull; <a href="https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2021/01/02/applied-category-theory-2021-adjoint-school/">Applied Category Theory 2021 Adjoint School</a>.</p>
<p>Also, my former student Brendan Fong has teamed up with David Spivak to set up a new institute, the <a href="https://topos.institute/" rel="nofollow ugc">Topos Institute</a>, for work along these lines.  They have $3.1 million in funding so far, but they&#8217;re just getting started.</p>
<p>I am not particularly interested in working on AI and AI risks, since so many smart people are already doing that, and I don&#8217;t feel I have any special skills in that area.   But it would definitely be good to talk to Tegmark.</p>
<p>After I retire in July, and already starting now, I plan to spend more time explaining math and physics&#8230; especially polishing up and packaging the explanations I&#8217;ve already written in <i>This Week&#8217;s Finds</i> and course notes.  My attempt to update the FAQ which you&#8217;re seeing here on Azimuth, is part of that.  But I actually got pulled into that particular little project because I was trying to understand neutrinos a bit better, to continue my project on <a href="https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2020/11/13/octonions-and-the-standard-model/">octonions and the Standard Model</a>.</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/about/?replytocom=168626#respond' data-commentid="168626" data-postid="2" data-belowelement="div-comment-168626" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to John Baez" aria-label='Reply to John Baez'>Reply</a></div>
				</div>
